b) Book the unaccounted transactions and ensure that all transactions have been duly recorded and the corresponding accounts been duly established; and
c) Reclassify the current portion of the Loans Payable – Domestic account.

1) Properly maintain the cashbooks pursuant to the prevailing regulations, especially on the recording, footing and reflecting the correct balances of the cash transactions, as well as the certification of the Municipal Treasurer at the end of each month;
2) Ensure that the financial transactions recorded are complete and accurate and should be reconciled monthly with the records of the accounting department in order to take up corrections or rectify errors as promptly as possible; and
3) Ensure that the figures recorded in the cashbooks are reflective of the transactions and that no other unnecessary figures have been included in the books.

1. Conduct a thorough analysis of the trust fund accounts, determine the dormant accounts that need to be reverted to the source agency, and coordinate with the implementing office with regard to the reversion of the unexpended balances;
2. Exert effort in tracing the origin of the accounts and coordinate with them in order to settle the unexpended balances; and
3. Coordinate with the source agency pertaining to the reversion of the unexpended balance and/or make a representation for any possible reprogramming of the said balances.

We recommended for the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Issue demand letters to all the accountable officers with outstanding unliquidated cash advances.
b. Make a representation to COA on the unliquidated cash advances which are more than 10 years for possible write-off after exhausting all means to collect;
c. Strictly comply with the provision of COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 on the required analysis of dormant accounts by performing periodic verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of receivable accounts and for possible request for write-off of the specified dormant receivables and cash advances to the Commission on Audit;
d. Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting entry to drop the said dormant accounts from the books.

The Local Chief Executive should:
a.) Identify clerical works authorized in different Local offices of the LGU and the necessity of hiring job order personnel;
b.) Align the hiring of job order personnel services with the authorized local projects.

We recommend the Local Chief Executive to instruct the concerned official/personnel to:
Consolidate the PPMPs submitted by the end-user Offices;
Implement strictly timelines on the posting and submission of procurement reports;
Establish procurement timelines in consonance with project schedules, including a cut-off date for processing requisitions and issuance of purchase orders to ensure receipt of most of the procured items in time for the project implementation;
Consider the strict observance of RA 9184 and its IRR, and other existing rules and regulation on government procurement as well as imposition of control measures to ensure that procurement is effected in an efficient, economical and effective manner that is most advantageous to the government and to prevent possible disallowances for such violation.
